Actually, it looks like this is just an incomplete fix of bug 115716. The fix is actually more simple than the attached patch.  
TextNodeFormatter#formatNode needs the following:
	try {
		lineDelimiter = doc.getLineDelimiter(line);
	}
	catch (BadLocationException e) {
		// log for now, unless we find reason not to
		Logger.log(Logger.INFO, e.getMessage());
	}
==>	// BUG166441: if cannot get line delimiter from current line, just
==>	// use default line delimiter
==>	if (lineDelimiter == null)
==>		lineDelimiter = doc.getLineDelimiter();

See bug 115716 comment 3 for explanation of fix.

No, this is not normal behaviour on any platform. This is very strange because "getFile()" just appends that string to a path, and getName() just returns the last segment in the path. I.e., this is equivalent to:

String name = "index.xml";
String name2 = Path.ROOT.append(name).lastSegment();
assertEquals("Names are not equal", name, name2);

Can you try the above snippet on your machine?

